<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BADB2F01CFDF11263" bold="true" box="[168,531,1028,1052]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="934760E6FFF7B54BAF01F01CFD7E1262" author="Elliot DG" box="[539,668,1028,1053]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" pagination="242 - 244" refId="ref13873" refString="Elliot DG (1870) Descriptions of some new genera and species of birds belonging to the families Formicariidae, Pachycephalidae, and Sylviidae. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 2: 242 - 244, pls 19, 20." type="book chapter" year="1870">Elliot, 1870</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, Southern
</emphasis>
Shrikebill: 
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BAC3AF03EFE4F1241" box="[288,429,1062,1087]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-10@10.[168,1419,160,1847]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Dark-brown Honeyeater Lichmera incana. B. Fan-tailed Gerygone Gerygone flavolateralis. C. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (male). D. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (female). E. Streaked Fantail Rhipidura verreauxi. F. Buff-bellied Monarch Neolalage banksiana. G. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (adult). H. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (immature)." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Figure 3G, H</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7691D17FFF7B54BADD4F051FE6611A8" blockId="11.[167,777,1028,2007]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">
The Southern Shrikebill occurs in 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BAF5FF051FD7E121F" box="[581,668,1097,1120]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BAFCEF051FEF412FC" name="New Caledonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BAC30F073FE6412FC" box="[298,390,1131,1155]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-10@10.[168,1419,160,1847]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Dark-brown Honeyeater Lichmera incana. B. Fan-tailed Gerygone Gerygone flavolateralis. C. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (male). D. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (female). E. Streaked Fantail Rhipidura verreauxi. F. Buff-bellied Monarch Neolalage banksiana. G. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (adult). H. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (immature)." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
). The 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BACC9F073FDC812FD" box="[467,554,1131,1154]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
subspecies (
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BAFA7F073FF3512DB" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">griscecens</emphasis>
) is found on most islands in the country, including throughout the Banks and Torres groups; however, it is absent from Tanna and Aneityum in the far south, as well as Ambrym in the heart of the archipelago. It is a bird of forest understory where it forages for insects in vine tangles. It is a medium-sized, uniformly brown passerine with a large, gray, hooked bill and dingy white tail tips. Its IUCN status is Least Concern. We observed it in 3 of our 4 survey sites. Curiously, we did not detect it on Éfaté where the WSSE collected 12 Southern Shrikebill in 
<date id="83683BD7FFF7B54BADD0F1FAFE4A1386" box="[202,424,1505,1530]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" value="1926-06" valueMax="1926-07-31" valueMin="1926-06-00">June and July 1926</date>
. The whistled vocalizations are similar to those of Buff-bellied Monarch so it is plausible we overlooked vocal birds on Éfaté. We had no trouble locating and capturing multiple individuals at our 3 subsequent camps on Malakula, Gaua, and Vanua Lava, which suggests it was at least inconspicuous or locally absent on Éfaté. Both male specimens from Malakula had enlarged testes and seminal vesicles with no evidence of molt, suggesting they were in breeding condition. Our observations on Gaua suggested birds had just completed nesting. We observed several family groups, including juveniles with black bills and yellow gape flanges (
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BAFC6F340FF2B11EC" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-10@10.[168,1419,160,1847]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Dark-brown Honeyeater Lichmera incana. B. Fan-tailed Gerygone Gerygone flavolateralis. C. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (male). D. Vanuatu Whistler Pachycephala chlorura (female). E. Streaked Fantail Rhipidura verreauxi. F. Buff-bellied Monarch Neolalage banksiana. G. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (adult). H. Southern Shrikebill Clytorhynchus pachycephaloides (immature)." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Fig. 3H</figureCitation>
) and 
<specimenCount id="E1D0D69EFFF7B54BAC1FF363FE9F11EC" box="[261,381,1915,1939]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" type="generic">1 specimen</specimenCount>
had a bursa of Fabricius (9 × 
<quantity id="302EB0F2FFF7B54BAFA0F363FD1E11EC" box="[698,764,1915,1939]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
). Three Gaua specimens were in molt. Stomach contents included arthropods.
</paragraph>
